The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                               SPORT BRIEFS
                  
	Islamabad: Former Test captain Aamer Sohail will head a three-member committee appointed by the Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) to look once again into The Oval Test fiasco of 2006.    
	The PCBs probe comes after the International Cricket Council (ICC) again amended the result of the August 2006 England-Pakistan Test at The Oval. Initially declared a Pakistan forfeit and England victory, the result was officially changed to a draw before the ICC decided last month that it would revert to the initial ruling.          
	Karachi: The Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) Friday wrote to the Indian Premier Leagues (IPL) drugs inquiry tribunal seeking to revise the period of the one-year ban imposed on Mohammed Asif for failing a dope test.          
	Karachi: The planned tri-series with Sri Lanka and Bangladesh scheduled to be held in Dubai in April has been postponed. The Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) chief operating officer Saleem Altaf said the event had been postponed by the organisers after Sri Lanka expressed their inability to take part.         
	Calcutta: Brad Haddin will lead Australia with Cameron White as his deputy in Sundays Twenty20 International against New Zealand at Sydney. The 12-member squad announced by Cricket Australia (CA) Friday features neither Michael Clarke nor Mitchell Johnson.           
	Calcutta: Brendon Diamanti and Peter Fulton were asked to stay back by New Zealand Cricket for the Twenty20 International against Australia after Kyle Mills was ruled out for pulling a right Achilles tendon.           
	Calcutta: Timir Ghosh will be the new vice-president of the CAB. The post fell vacant following the passing away of Arijit Roy, a couple of months back. The decision, however, will have to be ratified by the executive committee.     
	Meanwhile, Bankura and Siliguri won their matches in the inter-district Twenty20 meet on Friday.         
	Gurgaon: Mukesh Kumar blasted the best card of the final day, a five under 67, to register a comprehensive five-stroke victory and clinch Solaris Chemtech Open Golf Championship on Friday.        
	Open golf  
	Kuala Lumpur: Shiv Kapur rode a flawless front-nine to card three-under 69 and rise to tied 13th even though compatriots Gaurav Ghei and Digvijay Singh missed the cut in the Maybank Malaysian Open golf meet Friday.  
	Atwal tied 13th  
	California: Arjun Atwal rode a brilliant front-nine to card a four-under 68 for a share of the 13th spot after the opening round of the AT amp;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am golf meet.                                                                                                                                                                   
